Here's how you can implement this in Julia. Note that we are using the Statistics package for calculating average and trend:

```julia
using Statistics 

function weather_data_analyzer(temps)
    if isempty(temps)
        return (average = nothing, max = nothing, min = nothing, trend=nothing)
    elseif all(temp -> temp < temps[1], temps)
        return (average = mean(temps), max = temps[1], min = temps[1], trend=:decreasing) 
    elseif all(temp -> temp > temps[1], temps)
        return (average = mean(temps), max = temps[1], min = temps[1], trend=:increasing)
    else
        return (average = mean(temps), max = maximum(temps), min = minimum(temps), trend=:stable) 
    end
end
```
This function first checks if the list is empty. If it is, we return a named tuple with all values set to `nothing`. Then, it checks if all elements in `temps` are less than or equal to `temps[1]` (the first element of `temps`). If that's true, we return a named tuple with the average, max, and min set to `temps[1]`, while the trend is set to `:decreasing`. Similarly, if all elements in `temps` are greater than or equal to `temps[1]`, we set the average, max, and min to `temps[1]` and the trend to `:increasing`. If none of these conditions are met, we calculate and return the named tuple with the average, max, and min calculated from `temps` and the trend determined by whether or not `temps` is monotonically increasing/decreasing.
